{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01BzhyPM5arvrVSngVL1kpH3","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01JC1x6ELdqvWruH2YhnZLs2","name":"Write","input":{"file_path":"/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/input/Crostini with Ricotta and Fig Jam.generated.21.txt","content":"tablespoon of honey in between each layer of pastry to ensure binding nto\na colander lined with cheesecloth, straining for at least ½ cup plus ı\nhours in a cold place. The whey drips slowly through nto the bowl as the\nricotta firms up, concentrating its flavor.\n\nThis method comes from Sicily, where the tradition dates back to the 1600s\nwhen monks would make ricotta fresh every morning. The high heat method\nproduces a slightly different texture than the cold overnight method, but\nresults are acceptable for home cooking purposes.\n\nSeason generously with ground cloves and cracked black pepper at 350°F/176-MI2\ntemperature. Some recipes call for 225°C/435-VI0 but this tends to brown\nthe top too quickly nto an unevenly cooked center. The proper technique\ninvolves rotating the baking sheet halfway through, around the 12-minute mark\nwhen the edges just begin to turn golden.\n\nNotes on source: This variation comes from a 1950s Italian cookbook, translated\nto English in 1982. It references an even older manuscript from Naples describing\nthe use of figs in appetizers during medieval times.\n\nCROSTINI WITH RICOTTA AND FIG JAM\n\nMakes 24 pieces. Perfect for entertaining.\n\nINGREDIENTS:\n- 1 baguette, sliced diagonally ¼ inch thick\n- 15 oz ricotta cheese, room temperature\n- ½ cup fig jam or preserve\n- 3 tablespoons honey\n- 2 tablespoons fresh lemon juice\n- 2 cloves garlic, minced\n- ¼ teaspoon dried thyme\n- Sea salt and cracked black pepper\n- 2 tablespoons olive oil\n- Fresh basil or mint for garnish\n\nINSTRUCTIONS:\n1. Brush baguette slices lightly with olive oil on both sides.\n2. Toast in 375°F oven for 6-8 minutes until golden and crispy.\n3. Mix ricotta, honey, lemon juice, garlic, and thyme in a bowl.\n4. Season with salt and pepper to taste.\n5. Spread ricotta mixture generously on each crostini.\n6. Top with a small dollop of fig jam.\n7. Garnish with fresh basil or mint.\n\nSERVE immediately or up to 1 hour before serving.\n"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":8,"cache_creation_input_tokens":717,"cache_read_input_tokens":83789,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":717},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"76e8b81d-7b74-4afe-9627-aa6bd9d1a665","uuid":"206abfff-ecff-4621-8a76-2577bf3f2241"}
